<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Ohio packs several nationally respected nurse anesthesia programs into three major metro corridors — Cincinnati, Columbus, and Cleveland — plus strong options in Akron, Athens, and Youngstown. Here's how the Ohio programs compare and how an ICU nurse builds an application that earns an interview.</p>

<div class="hero-note">
<strong>Ohio CRNA market context:</strong> Ohio is home to two of the country's most prestigious health systems — Cleveland Clinic and the academic centers around the University of Cincinnati — which gives its CRNA students exceptional case volume and variety. New graduates in Ohio commonly start around $180,000–$205,000, with locum and rural assignments reaching higher. The state's program spread means most Ohio ICU nurses can train without leaving the state.
</div>

<h2>Accredited CRNA Programs in Ohio (2026)</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Program</th><th>Degree</th><th>Length</th><th>Location</th></tr>
<tr><td>University of Cincinnati</td><td>DNP (BSN-to-DNP)</td><td>36 months</td><td>Cincinnati</td></tr>
<tr><td>Case Western Reserve (Frances Payne Bolton)</td><td>DNP</td><td>36 months</td><td>Cleveland</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cleveland Clinic / Case Western partnership</td><td>DNP</td><td>36 months</td><td>Cleveland</td></tr>
<tr><td>The Ohio State University</td><td>DNP</td><td>36 months</td><td>Columbus</td></tr>
<tr><td>University of Akron</td><td>DNP</td><td>36 months</td><td>Akron</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ohio University</td><td>DNP</td><td>36 months</td><td>Athens</td></tr>
<tr><td>Youngstown State (St. Elizabeth partnership)</td><td>DNP</td><td>36 months</td><td>Youngstown</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Ohio offers roughly six to seven accredited programs depending on how partnerships are counted; Lourdes University is also sometimes listed. Every accredited Ohio program now awards a doctorate — the Council on Accreditation phased out master's-level CRNA entry on January 1, 2025. Confirm current tuition, credit counts, and clinical-hour requirements directly with each school.</p>

<h2>University of Cincinnati</h2>
<p>The University of Cincinnati College of Nursing offers a BSN-to-DNP with a major in nurse anesthesia and is one of the longest-running nurse anesthesia programs in the country. It consistently ranks among the top CRNA programs in the U.S. News &amp; World Report standings, drawing on the high-acuity environment of UC Medical Center and the broader Cincinnati academic system. For applicants who want a deeply established, top-ranked program in southern Ohio, UC is the anchor.</p>

<h2>Case Western Reserve and Cleveland Clinic</h2>
<p>Case Western's Frances Payne Bolton School of Nursing runs a university-based DNP in which students work one-on-one with a CRNA preceptor. A distinct Cleveland Clinic / Case Western partnership exists in which graduates receive their DNP and a nurse anesthesia certificate tied to the Cleveland Clinic — students across the two tracks share classroom and clinical space. The draw is obvious: Cleveland Clinic is one of the highest-volume cardiac and complex-surgery centers in the world, giving students extraordinary case exposure.</p>

<h2>Ohio State, Akron, Ohio University, and Youngstown State</h2>
<p>The Ohio State University's nurse anesthesia DNP in Columbus is COA-accredited and pairs with the high-acuity OSU Wexner Medical Center. The University of Akron has earned a perfect 10-year accreditation from the COA — a strong signal of program stability. Ohio University in Athens offers a COA-accredited DNP serving southeastern Ohio, and Youngstown State (in partnership with St. Elizabeth Health Center) anchors the northeastern corner of the state. Together these programs make it realistic for an Ohio ICU nurse to study close to home.</p>

<h2>Strong Ohio ICU Hospitals for CRNA Applicants</h2>
<p>Where you accumulate critical care hours matters as much as your GPA. Ohio offers several high-acuity systems ideal for CRNA candidacy:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Hospital</th><th>Metro</th><th>Notable ICU Types</th></tr>
<tr><td>Cleveland Clinic (main campus)</td><td>Cleveland</td><td>CVICU, transplant ICU, academic acuity</td></tr>
<tr><td>University Hospitals Cleveland Medical Center</td><td>Cleveland</td><td>CVICU, Neuro ICU, MICU/SICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>MetroHealth Medical Center</td><td>Cleveland</td><td>Level I Trauma, SICU, burn ICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>OSU Wexner Medical Center</td><td>Columbus</td><td>Level I Trauma, CVICU, Neuro ICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>University of Cincinnati Medical Center</td><td>Cincinnati</td><td>Level I Trauma, CVICU, Neuro ICU</td></tr>
<tr><td>Miami Valley Hospital</td><td>Dayton</td><td>Level I Trauma, CVICU, SICU</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Programs want sustained adult critical care managing ventilated patients on vasoactive infusions with arterial and central lines. A CVICU or trauma SICU role at one of these systems is far stronger on a CRNA application than a step-down or community "ICU" that does not manage that acuity.</p>

<h2>The Application Timeline from Ohio</h2>
<p>Working backward from a fall 2027 start: most Ohio programs accept applications roughly September–December 2026, interview January–March 2027, and decide by spring 2027. Have your CCRN completed and at least one year (ideally two) of high-acuity ICU hours documented before applications open. With programs in all three major metros, an Ohio applicant can apply to several in-state options plus one out-of-state without relocating during school.</p>

<div class="warning">
<strong>Competition concentrates at the top:</strong> Cincinnati, Case Western, and Ohio State draw national applicant pools and admit small cohorts. Don't apply only to the marquee names — pair a top-ranked reach program with one or two strong regional options (Akron, Ohio University, Youngstown State) where your in-state ICU experience and connections carry more weight.
</div>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Ohio CRNA salary on graduation:</strong> New CRNAs in Ohio metros commonly earn an estimated $180,000–$205,000 in hospital employment, with locum and rural assignments pushing higher. Cleveland, Columbus, and Cincinnati all carry steady surgical volume and anesthesia demand. See the <a href="crna-school-requirements-2026.html">CRNA school requirements guide</a> to benchmark your application before you apply, and the <a href="crna-school-cost-2026.html">CRNA school cost breakdown</a> to compare program financing.
</div>

